Yes -- that is a credible Beast direction.

The core idea is to factor the problem into stages instead of asking one model to solve identity, pose, motion, and temporal consistency all at once. That matches how current identity-preserving image methods and newer character-consistent video methods tend to work. InstantID is explicitly for zero-shot identity-preserving image generation from a single image, and IP-Adapter is a lightweight image-prompt adapter for diffusion models. Wan’s public model family includes image-to-video variants, which makes it a reasonable video stage in a multi-step Beast generator.  ￼

A strong Beast pipeline would look like this:

photo of self
→ extract character description
→ normalize to neutral pose still
→ generate controlled start / end stills
→ i2v with start/end + character descriptor
→ optional post-pass / upscale / sprite export

That is good architecture because each stage has one main job:
	•	identity extraction / anchoring
	•	canonical still generation
	•	pose control
	•	motion interpolation / video synthesis
	•	downstream packaging

Your "character descriptor improves video" insight is plausible. In practice, identity-preserving systems often work better when the model gets both a reference image signal and a text description signal, because the image holds fine identity features while the text stabilizes high-level traits like sex, age range, hair, clothing, and style. InstantID and IP-Adapter both point in that direction: image-based identity signal is strong, but text still matters for controllability.  ￼

Best technical split

1. Character description layer

Use either:
	•	user-entered description, or
	•	image-to-text / vision description from the reference photo

This description should be compressed and stable, not verbose. Example:

white male
middle aged
curly dark brown hair with gray
brown eyes
short beard
average build

This is not the primary identity source. It is the semantic anchor.

Rule:

photo = fine identity
description = semantic identity

That combination is stronger than either one alone. This fits how image-prompt systems and identity-preserving systems are typically used.  ￼

2. Neutral-pose canonical still

Take the input photo and run an I2I generator that converts it into a canonical neutral pose with:
	•	known framing
	•	known background
	•	known lighting class
	•	known body orientation

This is critical because it gives Beast a reusable "actor base frame."

Target:

same camera
same pose family
same background simplicity
same subject identity

This stage is where image-side identity methods like InstantID / IP-Adapter are most useful, because they are much better suited to preserving who the person is in a still than forcing full temporal consistency through a video model from scratch.  ￼

3. Pose-specific start and end stills

From the neutral pose still, generate:
	•	start frame
	•	end frame

These should keep:
	•	identity
	•	costume
	•	scene
	•	camera

while changing:
	•	pose
	•	expression maybe
	•	limb placement

This is cleaner than trying to go directly from one arbitrary selfie into a full video. It reduces the motion problem to a more bounded interpolation problem.

4. I2V stage

Feed:
	•	start still
	•	end still
	•	character descriptor
	•	motion / scene prompt

into the video stage.

This is where Wan I2V is a plausible backbone, because Wan explicitly supports image-to-video variants.  ￼

Your hypothesis is:

start + end + descriptor

is better than:

start + end only

That makes sense, because the descriptor can act like a guardrail against identity drift during temporal generation.

Strongest law for the generator

lock identity
lock framing
lock scene
vary pose and motion

If you do not lock framing and scene, the model will spend capacity changing things you do not want changed.

Suggested generator params

Something like:

$param: character-photo
$param: character-description
$param: neutral-style
$param: start-pose
$param: end-pose
$param: motion-template
$param: camera-template
$param: duration
$param: backend

And internally:

photo
→ identity / descriptor extraction
→ neutral still
→ start still
→ end still
→ i2v

Likely failure modes

These are the real ones:

1. Identity drift

Video model slowly "forgets" the face / body specifics.

Mitigation:
	•	stronger reference still
	•	stronger identity adapter in the image stages
	•	shorter clips first
	•	stable descriptor repeated in prompt
	•	tighter framing

2. Costume / hair mutation

Character keeps identity loosely but clothing or hair changes.

Mitigation:
	•	include costume in descriptor
	•	use neutral still with locked wardrobe
	•	keep background and pose conversion conservative

3. Start/end mismatch

If start and end are too different, the I2V stage may invent weird motion.

Mitigation:
	•	keep pose delta moderate
	•	chain short motions instead of giant transitions
	•	use reusable motion templates

4. Overfitting to face, underfitting to body

Common with identity methods built around portraits / faces.

Mitigation:
	•	full-body neutral still
	•	body description tokens
	•	full-body framing as a law

What to ship first

Not:

put anyone in any animation

Ship:

put a character into one of a few stable animation templates

Examples:
	•	pacing on stage
	•	idle turn
	•	walk loop
	•	speaking at camera

That is much easier to make reliable.

Closest external ideas

The broader research direction absolutely exists:
	•	identity-preserving image generation: InstantID, ConsistentID, IP-Adapter FaceID family  ￼
	•	character / identity-consistent video generation: Animate Anyone, MagicAnimate, SteadyDancer, Stand-In and related work  ￼

So Beast would not be inventing the research category from nothing. The real Beast move is to turn that messy space into a reusable generator abstraction.

Concise Beast architecture

identity anchor
+ semantic descriptor
+ canonical still
+ pose transform
+ i2v render
= reusable character animation generator

That is lgtm trending setm.

The most important implementation choice is probably this:

do not ask one model to solve everything at once

Split it into:
	•	image identity stabilization
	•	pose control
	•	video synthesis

That is the path most likely to make the demo actually work.









does onnx on mac do any optimizations out of the box? how long for one 512*512 sd image gen step expected on 2023ish intel mbp








Yes. On Mac, ONNX Runtime does do some optimization out of the box.

The big ones are:
	•	graph optimizations are enabled by default in the official packages, including constant folding, redundant-node elimination, and some fusions; ORT documents three optimization levels and says all are enabled by default.  ￼
	•	If you use the CoreML Execution Provider, ORT can target Apple’s CPU/GPU/Neural Engine path, but that provider must be explicitly registered; it is supported on macOS 10.15+, and ORT specifically says optimal performance is recommended on Apple devices with an Apple Neural Engine.  ￼
	•	By default, ORT places inputs and outputs on CPU, which can add copy overhead unless you use device binding.  ￼

For a 2023-ish Intel MacBook Pro, the practical read is:

ORT CPU path = yes
CoreML EP = mabe
fast Apple-Silicon-style acceleration = no, do not assume

because the CoreML docs explicitly steer "optimal performance" toward Apple devices with ANE, which Intel Macs do not have.  ￼

On timing: I can’t give you a trustworthy exact number without all of:
	•	exact model (sd1.5 vs sdxl)
	•	exact backend (CPU only vs CoreML EP)
	•	exact CPU / GPU in the Intel MBP
	•	whether this is one UNet denoise step or a full image

My rough engineering estimate for an Intel x86 MacBook Pro using plain ORT CPU execution is:

sd1.5 512x512
~1–5 seconds per denoise step

20 steps
~20–100 seconds total

That is a rough estimate, not a measured benchmark.

For SDXL, I would expect materially worse than that, often enough worse that it is not a pleasant local baseline on Intel laptop hardware.

So the short Beast answer is:

onnx on mac:
yes, some graph optimization by default

intel mbp:
usable for correctness / prototyping
not where i would expect fast sd generation

If you want a practical Beast rule:

intel mac:
ui + artifact graph + correctness check node

workstation / cloud:
canonical sd video/image heavy compute

And one more important nuance: on Mac, the "free" optimizations ORT gives you are mostly graph-level and some EP-level wins, not "magic GPU speedup." The graph side is real; the raw image-gen speed on an Intel MBP will still mostly be bounded by the hardware.  ￼







